            <p><strong>Mechanical Quality:</strong> Plastic body construction keeps weight low but feels less robust than metal housings. Focus mechanism smooth enough for practical use though not silky. Collimation generally holds but occasional sample variation exists. Rubber armoring provides decent grip. Not waterproof—avoid dew exposure or use dew shields.</p>
            <p><strong>Best For:</strong> First-time astronomy observers testing whether binocular observing appeals before larger investment. Budget-conscious students and casual observers. Secondary "grab and go" binoculars for experienced observers. Loaner binoculars for introducing friends to hobby.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Real-world performance impresses given the price. The Moon shows crisp craters and maria with moderate chromatic aberration along the limb. Jupiter appears as clear disc with four Galilean moons visible as tiny points. The Orion Nebula's central region glows greenish with Trapezium stars resolved in darker skies. The Pleiades cluster fills the field beautifully with 40-50 stars visible. Andromeda Galaxy appears as faint oval glow requiring dark skies and averted vision.</p>

