        <section id="specifications" class="content-section">
          <h2>Understanding Binocular Specifications</h2>
          <p>Binocular specifications communicate optical and mechanical characteristics through standardized format. Understanding these specifications enables informed purchasing decisions and realistic performance expectations.</p>

          <h3>Magnification and Aperture (10x50)</h3>
          <p>Binocular designation follows format: magnification × aperture. "10x50" indicates 10x magnification with 50mm objective lenses. Magnification shows how many times larger objects appear compared to naked eye viewing—at 10x, the Moon appears 10 times larger in diameter. Aperture (objective lens diameter in millimeters) determines light-gathering ability—larger apertures reveal fainter objects and gather more photons for brighter images.</p>

          <h3>Field of View</h3>
          <p>Field of view specifications come in two formats: angular (degrees) and linear (feet at 1,000 yards or meters at 1,000 meters). Angular field more useful for astronomy. A 6-degree field spans approximately 12 Moon-widths (Moon subtends 0.5 degrees). Conversion: 1 degree = 52.5 feet at 1,000 yards. Wider fields benefit astronomy through easier target location, better context preservation, and more immersive wide-field observing.</p>

          <p>True field of view decreases with increasing magnification—a 7x50 typically delivers 7-8 degree field while 10x50 delivers 5-6 degrees. Some manufacturers specify apparent field of view (eyepiece design-dependent) which determines true field when divided by magnification.</p>

          <h3>Exit Pupil</h3>
          <p>Exit pupil equals aperture divided by magnification (50mm ÷ 10x = 5mm exit pupil). This number indicates the diameter of the light beam exiting the eyepiece. Optimal exit pupil matches your dark-adapted pupil diameter (typically 5-7mm for younger observers, 4-5mm for older observers). Exit pupils larger than your eye pupil waste potential light; smaller exit pupils reduce brightness proportionally.</p>

          <h3>Eye Relief</h3>
          <p>Eye relief measures the distance between eyepiece lens and your eye where full field of view remains visible. Longer eye relief (15mm+) accommodates eyeglass wearers comfortably; shorter eye relief (10-13mm) forces eyeglass wearers to observe without glasses, potentially uncomfortable for astigmatism or severe prescriptions. Non-eyeglass wearers prefer 14-18mm eye relief for comfortable viewing without eyepiece pressure against eye orbit.</p>

          <h3>Close Focus Distance</h3>
          <p>Minimum focus distance (typically 3-20 meters) matters little for astronomy where all targets sit at effective infinity. However, shorter close focus enables terrestrial use (nature observation, birding) with same binoculars. Close focus under 6 meters allows multipurpose day/night use; 15+ meters limits practical daytime applications.</p>

          <h3>Optical Coatings</h3>
          <p>Coating specifications dramatically affect light transmission and image quality:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Coated:</strong> Single anti-reflection coating on some air-to-glass surfaces (cheapest, lowest performance, 80-85% transmission)</li>
            <li><strong>Fully Coated:</strong> Single coating on all air-to-glass surfaces (improved, 85-88% transmission)</li>
            <li><strong>Multi-Coated:</strong> Multiple coatings on some surfaces (better, 88-92% transmission)</li>
            <li><strong>Fully Multi-Coated:</strong> Multiple coatings on all air-to-glass surfaces (best standard, 92-95% transmission)</li>
            <li><strong>Premium Coatings:</strong> Advanced proprietary coatings (Fujinon EBC, Nikon Multi-Layer, Zeiss T*) achieve 95-98% transmission</li>
          </ul>

          <p>For astronomy, fully multi-coated minimum strongly recommended. Each percent of lost light reduces faint object visibility—difference between 85% and 95% transmission can mean seeing or missing faint galaxies.</p>

          <h3>Prism Glass Type</h3>
          <p>BaK-4 (barium crown glass) prisms deliver superior image quality with brighter images, better contrast, and rounder exit pupils compared to BK-7 (borosilicate) prisms. View through binoculars with eyepieces held away from eyes—circular exit pupils indicate BaK-4 prisms; square-cut exit pupils indicate cheaper BK-7 prisms. For astronomy, BaK-4 prisms strongly preferred. Premium models add phase coatings (roof prisms only) and dielectric coatings for enhanced contrast.</p>

          <h3>Interpupillary Distance (IPD)</h3>
          <p>IPD adjustment range (typically 56-74mm) must accommodate your personal interpupillary distance (spacing between your eyes' pupils). Most adults fall within standard ranges, but individuals with very wide-set (75mm+) or very close-set (55mm-) eyes should verify binocular adjustment range accommodates their IPD. Children and some adults with narrow IPD may struggle with full-size binoculars; compact models often adjust to narrower IPD.</p>

          <h3>Weight and Balance</h3>
          <p>Weight significantly affects handheld viewing comfort and duration. Guideline recommendations: 700-900g comfortable for extended handheld use; 900-1,200g manageable for moderate handheld sessions (15-20 minutes) before fatigue; 1,200-1,500g brief handheld viewing only—tripod preferred; 1,500g+ tripod essential. Weight distribution and balance matter as much as absolute weight—poorly balanced binoculars cause faster fatigue than well-balanced slightly heavier models.</p>
